<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910920-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>910920-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Bush Urged to Reconsider   Nominee for Comptroller</HL><DATE>09/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)EXECUTIVE (EXE)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Senate Banking Committee Chairman DonaldRiegle urged the Bush administration to reconsider itsdecision to nominate Robert Clarke to a second five-year termas Comptroller of the Currency.   The large number of bank failures during Mr. Clarke'sfirst term as national bank supervisor shows &quot;a seriousbreakdown in the regulatory process,&quot; Sen. Riegle (D., Mich.)charged. &quot;I think the administration needs to think long andhard about this nomination.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   White House spokesman Gary Foster said, &quot;The president isstanding by his nominee.&quot; He added that he hoped Mr. Clarkewould receive a &quot;fair and good hearing&quot; before the committee.   Mr. Riegle made his remarks after hearing Charles Bowsher,the head of the General Accounting Office, outline a GAOfinding that the Comptroller's office didn't act aggressivelyenough to force the Bank of New England to correct riskylending and other unsound practices. The bank's Januaryfailure will cost the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.'s BankInsurance Fund an estimated $2.5 billion.   At yesterday's hearing, Democrats and one Republican, Sen.Alphonse D'Amato of New York, attacked Mr. Clarke's record,making it clear that he will face a grilling when hisconfirmation hearing starts next Thursday.   Despite his stern comments, however, Mr. Riegle refused tosay whether he plans to oppose the nomination.</TEXT></DOC>